1
00:00:00,110 --> 00:00:05,360
In this video we are going to learn benefits of asynchronous communication.

2
00:00:05,570 --> 00:00:08,930
The first benefit is adding new subscriber services.

3
00:00:08,930 --> 00:00:12,110
So adding new subscriber services is very simple.

4
00:00:12,110 --> 00:00:15,770
We can easily subscribe to a message that we want to receive.

5
00:00:16,010 --> 00:00:19,610
The producer doesn't need to be know about subscribers.

6
00:00:19,610 --> 00:00:24,470
We can remove and add subscribers without affecting producer service.

7
00:00:25,120 --> 00:00:27,460
And another benefit is scalability.

8
00:00:28,120 --> 00:00:34,180
When services communicate with direct sync communications, if the servers get high volume requests,

9
00:00:34,180 --> 00:00:40,750
these communication parties should be scaled together and at the same time, so it is hard to maintain

10
00:00:40,750 --> 00:00:42,400
high volume peak requests.

11
00:00:43,030 --> 00:00:47,680
With asynchronous communication, we can easier to manage scalability issues.

12
00:00:47,680 --> 00:00:54,850
We can scale producer, consumer and message broker system independently, so we can also scale services

13
00:00:54,850 --> 00:00:57,940
according to incoming messages into event based system.

14
00:00:58,570 --> 00:01:03,850
The message broker can distribute the received message to more than one target services.

15
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:10,780
If incoming message are increased into message broker system, we can scale consumer services and receive

16
00:01:10,780 --> 00:01:13,510
messages faster in microservices.

17
00:01:13,510 --> 00:01:20,830
Kubernetes has autoscaler that we can define maximum port number according to CPU and Ram usage into

18
00:01:20,830 --> 00:01:22,000
current instance.

19
00:01:22,210 --> 00:01:28,570
But also there is another good product which is the Keda, which is a Kubernetes event driven application

20
00:01:28,570 --> 00:01:32,890
that we can auto scale pods according to message broker system loads.

21
00:01:32,980 --> 00:01:40,930
For example, if our microservice architecture uses Kafka, and if Kafka has more messages that we expected

22
00:01:40,930 --> 00:01:46,900
with using the Keda, we can auto scale consumer microservices automatically.

23
00:01:47,050 --> 00:01:53,170
So asynchronous communication is allowed to be more flexible in terms of the scalability issues.

24
00:01:54,290 --> 00:01:57,410
And another benefit is event driven microservices.

25
00:01:57,410 --> 00:02:02,900
With asynchronous communication, we can provide event driven architectures, which is the best way

26
00:02:02,900 --> 00:02:09,229
to communicate between microservices services, communicates with each other by creating events and

27
00:02:09,229 --> 00:02:14,600
send events to message broker, event bus system and subscribe events from the microservices.

